  abstract = {In this paper we study a spectrum \$K(\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft V\textbraceright\_k)\$ such that \$\textbackslash pi\_0 K(\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft V\textbraceright\_k)\$ is the Grothendieck ring of varieties and such that the higher homotopy groups contain more geometric information about the geometry of varieties. We use the topology of this spectrum to analyze the structure of \$K\_0[\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft V\textbraceright\_k]\$ and show that classes in the kernel of multiplication by \$[\textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft A\textbraceright\textasciicircum 1]\$ can always be represented as \$[X]-[Y]\$ where \$X\$ and \$Y\$ are varieties such that \$[X] \textbackslash neq [Y]\$, \$X\textbackslash times \textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft A\textbraceright\textasciicircum 1\$ and \$Y\textbackslash times \textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft A\textbraceright\textasciicircum 1\$ are not piecewise isomorphic, but \$[X\textbackslash times \textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft A\textbraceright\textasciicircum 1] =[Y\textbackslash times \textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft A\textbraceright\textasciicircum 1]\$ in \$K\_0[\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft V\textbraceright\_k]\$. Along the way we present new proofs of the result of Larsen--Lunts on the structure on \$K\_0[\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft V\textbraceright\_k]/([\textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft A\textbraceright\textasciicircum 1])\$.},
